      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "756c0041f1c9cf1c",
      "text": "# On People\nWe believe that:\n* People are the primary asset of any organisation\n* People’s social abilities such as interacting, building trust, making sense, building consensus, and ultimately collaborating and co-creating, are the fabric of an organisation \n* Each individual is unique and has unique skills, experiences, and capabilities that are assets to be preserved and promoted\n* People’s creativity, intelligence, initiative and free-will are essential and need to be safeguarded, promoted, and rewarded\n* We need to hire smart creators and changers and trust them to do the right thing \n* In the organisation we are all equal as thinkers\n* The attention to the people is reflected also in the organisation’s mission of delighting customers\n* What ultimately happens in the organisation is the result of emergent patterns of action arising in the interplay of choices made by many different individuals and groups of people also from outside the organisation, in a constantly evolving dynamic that cannot be controlled nor predicted but only influenced\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d3725dace1dd7154",
      "text": "# On Structure\nWe believe that:\n* All the authority needed to get the job done should always be given to those with the responsibility to do the job\n* Information should be shared by default on a need-to-share basis\n* The basic building blocks of the organisation are the relationships between the members of every autonomous cross-functional team, and their integrity should be preserved over time\n* Loosely coupled autonomous cross-functional teams should be clustered around each organisation’s product or service or value-stream\n* A rigid or deep hierarchy obstructs relevant information sharing, prevents the alignment of authority with responsibility, constrains effective collaboration, and delays decision making.\nA flat, flexible and networked organisation accelerate information sharing, dynamic re-alignment of authority and responsibility, promote collaboration and allow for quick decision making\n* Combining the collective partial-understandings of the organisation, raising situational awareness and adopting a holistic view is the best possible way to get to know and understand more an organisation"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "614f0ce0dbfbfd85",
      "text": "# On Ways of Working\nWe believe that:\n* Uncertainty, unknowns, change and risks that cannot be statistically quantified nor anticipated are the norm when solving complex problems\n* Inspecting, adapting and evolving our ways of working are ever ongoing activities, and every operating model is an incomplete draft in constant emergent evolution\n* Learning and delivering are two intertwined activities informing supporting each other, in a process of coevolution\n* Speed, productivity and volume are achieved through simplicity, starting small, working in small batches, maximising the flow of work completed and the outcomes achieved, and via gradual emergent refinements  through a cycle of experimentation-learning-adaptation-evolution\n* Speed, productivity and volume are achieved through the highest quality, technical excellence, and seamless collaboration between the business and the tech.\n* The short and fast cycles of the iterative ways of working should encompass the organisation’s strategic goals ideation throughout the delivery and the achievement of the desired business impact breaking down all the silos across functions, roles and all the levels in the hierarchy \n* The wisdom of the crowd, collective intelligence, collaboration and co-creation are fundamental when defining a strategy, deciding which initiatives and experiments are to be financed, and prioritising which opportunities should be prioritised"
    }
